'''John Fallowfield Townsend Toppin''' ([[25 February]] [[1900]] - [[22 November]] [[1965]]) was an [[England|English]] [[cricketer]] who played a single [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match, for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] at [[Old Trafford (cricket)|Old Trafford]] in 1920. He scored 2 and 6, and bowled two overs without reward.

Toppin was born in [[Great Malvern]], [[Worcestershire]] and attended [[Winchester School]], playing for the cricket XI there. He died aged 65 in [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]], [[Berkshire]].

A number of his relations played first-class cricket. His father, [[Charles Toppin (Cambridge University cricketer)|Charles Toppin]], played 25 times (mostly for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]]) in the late 19th century; his brother, also named [[Charles Toppin (Worcestershire cricketer)|Charles]], played a few games for Worcestershire in the late 1920s; while three uncles &mdash; [[Arthur Day]], [[Sam Day]] and [[Sydney Day]] &mdash; had careers of varying lengths with [[Kent County Cricket Club|Kent]].

